{"id":"2108.08223","submitter":"Erik Orvehed Hiltunen","authors":"Habib Ammari, Francesco Fiorani, Erik Orvehed Hiltunen","title":"On the validity of the tight-binding method for describing systems of\n  subwavelength resonators","comments":"25 pages, 2 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.AP cond-mat.mtrl-sci","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The goal of this paper is to relate the capacitance matrix formalism to the\ntight-binding approximation. By doing so, we open the way to the use of\nmathematical techniques and tools from condensed matter theory in the\nmathematical and numerical analysis of metamaterials, in particular for the\nunderstanding of their topological properties. We firstly study how the\ncapacitance matrix formalism, both when the material parameters are static and\nmodulated, can be posed in a Hamiltonian form. Then, we use this result to\ncompare this formalism to the tight-binding approximation. We prove that the\ncorrespondence between the capacitance formulation and the tight-binding\napproximation holds only in the case of dilute resonators. On the other hand,\nthe tight-binding model is often coupled with a nearest-neighbour\napproximation, whereby long-range interactions are neglected. Even in the\ndilute case, we show that long-range interactions between subwavelength\nresonators are relatively strong and nearest-neighbour approximations are not\ngenerally appropriate.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 18 Aug 2021 16:17:23 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-08-19"}
